he mythic image, from the late 1870s on, as the Texas frontier became more settled and the open range disappeared, the real cowboys faced increasing demands from the people around them to rein in the very traits that Americans considered the most masculine.Published in Cooperation with the William P. Clements Center for Southwest Studies, Southern Methodist University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCattle tradexSocial aspectszTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aCowboyszTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aFrontier and pioneer lifezTexas. 0aMasculinityzTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aRanch lifezTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aRancherszTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aSex rolezTexasxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial classeszTexasxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814759844423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814759844.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK